<DOC><DOCNO> AP880405-0255 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 0828EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-KansasCitySouthern     04-05 0251</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Kansas City Southern,0259</SECOND><HEAD>Hallmark Joins With KCSI To Turn Back Buy-Out</HEAD><DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Kansas City Southern Industries Inc. andHallmark Cards Inc. have paid investor Howard Kaskel $77.6 millionfor his 11.3 percent stake in Kansas City Southern.   In return, Kaskel ended a nearly eight-month pursuit of KansasCity Southern.   Kansas City Southern bought 54 percent of Kaskel's stock, or694,000 shares, for $41.6 million while Hallmark bought theremaining 600,600 shares for $36 million.   If approved by regulators, Hallmark's purchase will make itKansas City Southern's largest stockholder, with 1.04 millionshares, or 9.4 percent of those outstanding. The Kansas City-basedgreeting card giant said it liked Kansas City Southern's long-termprospects and didn't plan to take control.   Hallmark, which is closely held, previously owned 4 percent ofKansas City Southern's stock. Irvine O. Hockaday Jr., president andchief executive officer of Hallmark, held a similar position atKansas City Southern from 1981 until 1983.   The buy-out alliance between the companies was forged quicklyand sealed Sunday or Monday, Kansas City Southern spokesman FredSpar said.   A spokesman for Kaskel said he sold out because he was notinterested in pursuing a hostile takeover.   Kaskel proposed a friendly buyout of the Kansas City Southernshares that his group didn't own for $587.6 million, or $60 apiece.The offer was spurned and Kaskel threatened a proxy battle to nametwo of his group to the board of directors at Kansas CitySouthern's annual meeting May 3.</TEXT></DOC>